Every byte transmitted in TCP receives a sequence number.

The Initial Sequence Number (ISN) is randomly generated during connection establishment.

Sequence numbers allow TCP to:

reorder packets
detect missing data
retransmit lost segments
Cybersecurity Relevance

Predictable sequence numbers historically enabled TCP session hijacking and spoofing attacks. Modern operating systems randomize ISNs to prevent this.

Tools
Wireshark
Scapy
tcpdump
Blue Team (Defenders)

Process: Verify TCP state consistency and rely on randomized ISNs provided by modern operating systems.

End Goal: Prevent spoofed packets from joining legitimate sessions.

Red Team (Attackers)

Process: Attempt TCP session hijacking by injecting forged packets into active connections.

End Goal: Impersonate one endpoint and inject malicious commands.
